‚ô•
Jun 26, 2018 11:54pm
Karen Yang
you are such a great teacher
Jun 26, 2018 11:54pm
Nikhil Buduma
the rest of the cells in the blood are normal, healthy cells with what should be a relatively normal genome
Jun 26, 2018 11:50pm
Nikhil Buduma
the goal of the liquid biopsy is to find these variants even though only a small fraction of the cellular DNA (ref point 1 above), hails from the cancer and therefore harbors the mutations in question
Jun 26, 2018 11:50pm
Nikhil Buduma
if your read depth is 10, or even better 50, then you can be more confident in your characterization of the locus
Jun 26, 2018 11:48pm
Nikhil Buduma
if your read depth is 1, then it's really hard to tell if a difference between the sample and reference genome is due to sequencing errors
Jun 26, 2018 11:48pm
Nikhil Buduma
the more reads that you have that traverse over a particular locus, the more signal you have in trying to estimate what mutation (if any) that locus harbors
Jun 26, 2018 11:47pm
Nikhil Buduma
Read depth is a variable that describes, on average, how many reads cover a given base pair in the genome
Jun 26, 2018 11:47pm
Nikhil Buduma
does this make sense?
Jun 26, 2018 11:45pm
Nikhil Buduma
A variant caller is a piece of software that is meant to take into account these considerations, and ingest a reference genome + reads from a next generation sequencing experiment and produce the exact base pair locations in the genome where the sample being analyzed has a difference from the reference genome
Jun 26, 2018 11:45pm
Nikhil Buduma
2) there may be sequencing errors on a per read (or per fragment) basis because DNA polymerase isn't a perfect enzyme
Jun 26, 2018 11:44pm
Nikhil Buduma
1) some cells may have mutations in them, so not all of the cells have the exact same DNA
Jun 26, 2018 11:43pm
Nikhil Buduma
now the world isn't perfect and two major considerations come into play
Jun 26, 2018 11:43pm
Nikhil Buduma
if you have a mutation in both copies of the chromosome, you expect all of the reads to have different base pairs
Jun 26, 2018 11:43pm
Nikhil Buduma
if you have a mutation in one copy of the chromosome you expect half of the reads to have a different base pair from the reference genome
Jun 26, 2018 11:42pm
Nikhil Buduma
and so if you have no mutations, you expect at a particular locus (nucleotide location) that all of the reads (DNA fragments) have the same base pair
Jun 26, 2018 11:42pm
Nikhil Buduma
and every fragment of DNA was sequenced perfectly
Jun 26, 2018 11:41pm
Nikhil Buduma
you have two copies of each chromosome (except X, Y if you're male)
Jun 26, 2018 11:41pm
Nikhil Buduma
In a perfect world, every single cell has the exact same DNA
Jun 26, 2018 11:41pm
Nikhil Buduma
Now how do you know whether there's a difference?
Jun 26, 2018 11:40pm
Nikhil Buduma
once all the fragments are aligned you can impute the sequence (and differences from the reference genome)
Jun 26, 2018 11:40pm
Nikhil Buduma
you get something that looks like this
Jun 26, 2018 11:40pm
Nikhil Buduma
Jun 26, 2018 11:40pm
Nikhil Buduma
https://qph.fs.quoracdn.net/main-qimg-4ce2e4500bc8b879980528f011d9ccf8
Jun 26, 2018 11:39pm
Nikhil Buduma
by doing a best match search
Jun 26, 2018 11:38pm
Nikhil Buduma
then you align each of those fragments back to a reference genome
Jun 26, 2018 11:38pm
Nikhil Buduma
and then you sequence those fragments
Jun 26, 2018 11:38pm
Nikhil Buduma
into small fragments
Jun 26, 2018 11:38pm
Nikhil Buduma
so the way sequencing works is that you break up all of the DNA

Nikhil Buduma

I don‚Äôt cry around people anymore. It‚Äôs not that I won‚Äôt, but that I can‚Äôt. Company mutes my lows. I don‚Äôt mean that being surrounded by people makes me happy. Well I wouldn‚Äôt call it that, anyway. It‚Äôs more a lack of feeling than any particular feeling at all. Emptiness, maybe. I‚Äôm not sure.

When I‚Äôm alone, I‚Äôm flooded with thoughts. Uncomfortable thoughts. Narratives of tender moments meant to come. Or, at least, moments that I hoped one day would. I don‚Äôt think they‚Äôre coming anymore.

I caress those thoughts in my mind. My mother used to tell me that if I exerted myself appropriately, I could will any thought into existence. Maybe I‚Äôm still hung up on the possibility that she was right. Maybe I‚Äôm too afraid to live in a world where she was wrong.

I am an amalgamation of dangling stories, grasping for resolution. I find that writing new ones is much like living on borrowed time. Inevitability catches up. I wallow in it. But I‚Äôm not sure I‚Äôd want differently, even if I could.

3) We‚Äôve grown up in a world with a rather pervasive assumption: that humans are the source of economic value creation. This assumption, embedded in a world that runs on capitalism, has led to a very specific way of growing up. We go to school to get a degree to get a job to make ends meet for our families. This is the core of our identify and a driving narrative behind fulfillment for nearly every person alive in this country. I tend to be of the opinion that AGI is impending, and whether you think it‚Äôs coming in 15 years (like Greg Brockman) or 50 years (myself), as more and more people find their livelihoods more effectively executed by machines, the less relevant it becomes to construct our lives around this particular educational path. It becomes far more important to discover how to live a fulfilling life in other ways. And if we want to be prepared for a 30 year time horizon in terms of education, lots of these changes need to happen in the next decade in education.
